Title: Durability of Output and Expected Stock Returns
Abstract: The demand for durable goods is more cyclical than that for nondurable goods and services. Consequently, the cash flows and stock returns of durable&hyphen;good producers are exposed to higher systematic risk. Using the benchmark input&hyphen;output accounts of the National Income and Product Accounts, we construct portfolios of durable&hyphen;good, nondurable&hyphen;good, and service producers. In the cross section, an investment strategy that is long on the durable&hyphen;good portfolio and short on the service portfolio earns a risk premium exceeding 4 percent annually. In the time series, an investment strategy that is long on the durable&hyphen;good portfolio and short on the market portfolio earns a countercyclical risk premium. We explain these findings in a general equilibrium asset&hyphen;pricing model with endogenous production.
